<BaseLayout title="About the Project" activeSection="about">

  <section style="background: #0f1419; padding: 4rem 1rem;">
    <div style="max-width: 48rem; margin: 0 auto; text-align: center;">
      <p style="font-family: sans-serif; color: #c9a84c; font-size: 0.7rem; text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.2em; margin-bottom: 1rem;">Erasmus+ KA171 Project</p>
      <h1 style="font-family: 'Cormorant Garamond', serif; color: #faf5ee; font-size: 2.2rem; font-weight: 600; line-height: 1.3;">
        Exploring Intersections: Buddhism, Christianity, Confucianism, and Natural Science in the Age of AI
      </h1>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section style="max-width: 48rem; margin: 0 auto; padding: 3rem 1rem;">
    <div style="font-family: 'Lora', serif; color: #44403c; font-size: 1rem; line-height: 1.8;">

      <h2 style="font-family: 'Cormorant Garamond', serif; font-size: 1.5rem; font-weight: 600; color: #1c1917; margin-bottom: 1rem;">The Partnership</h2>
      <p style="margin-bottom: 1rem;">
        This resource is a product of the Erasmus+ KA171 international credit mobility partnership
        between the <strong>Evangelical Lutheran Theological Faculty (EBF UK)</strong> at Comenius University
        in Bratislava, Slovakia, and the <strong>Tran Nhan Tong Institute (TNTI)</strong> at Vietnam
        National University in Hanoi, Vietnam. The project runs from August 2025 through July 2028.
      </p>
      <p style="margin-bottom: 1rem;">
        The collaboration was initiated through joint participation in two projects funded by the
        John Templeton Foundation, led by Prof. Michal Valčo. The first project focused on
        "Imago Dei Theological Anthropologies and Transhumanism" (2022–2023). Building on this foundation,
        the Erasmus+ partnership enables teacher and student exchanges across theology, philosophy, ethics,
        and religious studies, with English as the working language.
      </p>

      <h2 style="font-family: 'Cormorant Garamond', serif; font-size: 1.5rem; font-weight: 600; color: #1c1917; margin: 2rem 0 1rem;">The Research Focus</h2>
      <p style="margin-bottom: 1rem;">
        The joint research project explores intersections of Buddhist, Christian, and Confucian
        philosophical traditions with the natural sciences — specifically in the context of artificial
        intelligence and its ethical implications. The approach is genuinely interdisciplinary:
        each tradition is engaged on its own terms, using what Alister McGrath calls <em>colligation</em>
        — bringing together insights from across intellectual disciplines without reducing any one
        perspective to the others.
      </p>

      <h2 style="font-family: 'Cormorant Garamond', serif; font-size: 1.5rem; font-weight: 600; color: #1c1917; margin: 2rem 0 1rem;">This Resource</h2>
      <p style="margin-bottom: 1rem;">
        The presentation "Science, Creation, Contingency, and the Human Person" was delivered on
        March 12, 2026, at the Tran Nhan Tong Institute as part of an Erasmus+ Staff Training Mobility.
        At the request of the TNTI faculty, this website expands the lecture into an interactive
        scholarly resource with deeper content, visual learning aids, and structured dialogue points
        between Christian and Buddhist perspectives.
      </p>

      <h2 style="font-family: 'Cormorant Garamond', serif; font-size: 1.5rem; font-weight: 600; color: #1c1917; margin: 2rem 0 1rem;">Key People</h2>
      <p style="margin-bottom: 0.5rem;"><strong>Project Coordinator:</strong> prof. PhDr. Michal Valčo, PhD. — Evangelical Lutheran Theological Faculty, Comenius University (<a href="mailto:michal.valco@uniba.sk" style="color: #c9a84c;">michal.valco@uniba.sk</a>)</p>
      <p style="margin-bottom: 0.5rem;"><strong>Partner Contact:</strong> Dao Thi Tam Khanh — Deputy Head of Education and Research, Tran Nhan Tong Institute, VNU Hanoi</p>
      <p style="margin-bottom: 0.5rem;"><strong>Faculty Coordinator (EBF UK):</strong> Mgr. Maroš Nicák, Dr. theol.</p>

